Date:8/17/2011 1:16:36 PM
From:E_K_S
Hi Difco -

Re: Friedman Industries Inc. (FRD)

It appears that growth is organic specific to their region (ie. Texas). They
are such a small company that most any sustained increase in their sales moves
the meter. I did go through the information they have on their Web site and saw
nothing too out of the ordinary. I do know that Texas is one of a few states
that is experiencing growth so the specialty steel products that this company
provides sells right into the current growth sectors (ie Oil & AG). Maybe part
of their current spike in sales could be related to the sustained drought Texas
is going through. There is always the need for more irrigation pipe, and water
well related piping.

I discovered this company using a value screen on FINVIZ. You can play around
with the variable screen setting(s) and see what other similar types of
companies come up. http://finviz.com/screener.ashx?v=111&t=frd

I originally was looking for specialty steel piping companies that service the
growing U.S. Oil & NG shale regions.

The one big problem with FRD is it is a Micro Cap, the stock is thinly traded
and if any large share holder wants out, the stock will sell off until the
shares are absorbed in the market. This has occurred w/ the stock trading down
to $8.00/share from $12.00/share w/i the past 10 trading secessions.

EKS
